
<handout xml:id="handout-section-2-1-matrix-algebra">
  <title>2.1 Matrix Operations</title>

  <page xml:id="p-2-1-overview">
    <title>Topics and Objectives</title>

    <objectives>
        <title>Topics</title>
    <ul>
      <li>Identity and zero matrices</li>
      <li>Matrix algebra (sums and products, scalar multiplies, matrix powers)</li>
      <li>Transpose of a matrix</li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>

    <objectives workspace="true">
        <title>Goals</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <em>Apply</em> matrix algebra, the matrix transpose, and the zero and identity matrices,
        to <em>solve</em> and <em>analyze</em> matrix equations.
      </li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>


    <definition xml:id="def-zero-matrix" workspace="true">
      <title>Zero Matrix</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>zero matrix</term> is any matrix whose every entry is zero.
        </p>
        <me>
          0_{2\times 3}=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          0_{2\times 1}=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            0\\
            0
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>


    <definition xml:id="def-identity-matrix" workspace="true">
      <title>Identity Matrix</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The <m>n\times n</m> <term>identity matrix</term> has ones on the main diagonal and zeros elsewhere.
        </p>
        <me>
          I_2=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 1
          \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          I_3=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 1
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <p>
      Note: Any matrix with dimensions <m>n\times n</m> is <term>square</term>.
      Zero matrices need not be square; identity matrices must be square.
    </p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-1-sums-scalars">
    <title>Sums and Scalar Multiples</title>

    <p>
      Suppose <m>A\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times n}</m>, and <m>a_{i,j}</m> is the element of <m>A</m>
      in row <m>i</m> and column <m>j</m>.
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> are <m>m\times n</m> matrices, then the elements of <m>A+B</m>
          are <m>a_{i,j}+b_{i,j}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>c\in\mathbb{R}</m>, then the elements of <m>cA</m> are <m>c\,a_{i,j}</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

    <example xml:id="ex-sum-scalar-find-c-k" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If
        </p>
        <me>
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 2 \amp 3\\
            4 \amp 5 \amp 6
          \end{bmatrix}
          + c
          \begin{bmatrix}
            7 \amp 4 \amp 7\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp k
          \end{bmatrix}
          =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            15 \amp 10 \amp 17\\
            4 \amp 5 \amp 16
          \end{bmatrix},
        </me>
        <p>
          what are the values of <m>c</m> and <m>k</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-1-properties-addition-scalars">
    <title>Properties of Sums and Scalar Multiples</title>

    <p>
      Scalar multiples and matrix addition have the expected properties.
      If <m>r,s\in\mathbb{R}</m> are scalars and <m>A,B,C</m> are <m>m\times n</m> matrices, then:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li><m>A + 0_{m\times n} = A</m></li>
      <li><m>(A+B)+C = A+(B+C)</m></li>
      <li><m>r(A+B)=rA+rB</m></li>
      <li><m>(r+s)A = rA + sA</m></li>
      <li><m>r(sA) = (rs)A</m></li>
    </ol>


    <definition xml:id="def-matrix-multiplication-columns" workspace="true">
      <title>Matrix Product via Columns</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m\times n</m> matrix and <m>B</m> be an <m>n\times p</m> matrix.
          The product <m>AB</m> is an <m>m\times p</m> matrix, given by
        </p>
        <me>
          AB
          =
          A
          \begin{bmatrix}
            \vec b_1 \amp \cdots \amp \vec b_p
          \end{bmatrix}
          =
          \begin{bmatrix}
            A\vec b_1 \amp \cdots \amp A\vec b_p
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p>
      Note: The dimensions of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> determine whether <m>AB</m> is defined,
      and what its dimensions will be.
    </p>

    <image xml:id="img-matrix-multiplication-dimensions" source="./matrix_multi2.png" width="40%">
      <shortdescription>Diagram showing how matrix dimensions match in a product.</shortdescription>
      <description>
        A visual guide to when <m>AB</m> is defined based on inner dimensions.
      </description>
    </image>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-1-row-column-rule">
    <title>Row-Column Rule</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-row-column-rule">
      <title>Row-Column Rule for Matrix Multiplication</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>A\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times n}</m> has rows <m>\vec a_i</m> and
          <m>B\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times p}</m> has columns <m>\vec b_j</m>, then each element of
          <m>C=AB</m> is
        </p>
        <me>
          c_{ij}=\vec a_i\cdot \vec b_j.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <example xml:id="ex-row-column-compute" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Compute the following using the row-column method.</p>
        <me>
          C=AB=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            2 \amp 0\\
            1 \amp -1
          \end{bmatrix}
          \begin{bmatrix}
            3 \amp 0 \amp 1\\
            4 \amp 5 \amp 6
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-1-properties-multiplication">
    <title>Properties and Warnings</title>
    <theorem workspace="true">
        <title> Properties and Warnings</title>
            <p>
            Let <m>A,B,C</m> be matrices of sizes needed for the products to be defined,
            and suppose <m>A</m> is <m>m\times n</m>.
            </p>

            <ol>
            <li><p><em>Associative:</em> <m>(AB)C = A(BC)</m></p></li>
            <li><p><em>Left distributive:</em> <m>A(B+C)=AB+AC</m></p></li>
            <li><p><em>Right distributive:</em> <m>(A+B)C = AC + BC</m></p></li>
            <li><p><em>Identity:</em> <m>I_m A = A I_n</m></p></li>
            </ol>

            <p><em>Warnings:</em></p>
            <ol>
            <li>
                <p><em>Non-commutative:</em> In general, <m>AB\neq BA</m>.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p><em>Non-cancellation:</em> <m>AB=AC</m> does not imply <m>B=C</m>.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p><em>Zero divisors:</em> <m>AB=0</m> does not imply <m>A=0</m> or <m>B=0</m>.</p>
            </li>
            </ol>
        </theorem>

    <p>
      The associative property is <m>(AB)C = A(BC)</m>. If <m>C=\vec x</m>, then:
    </p>

    <me>(AB)\vec x = A(B\vec x).</me>

    <p>Schematically:</p>

    <image xml:id="img-associative-flow" width="70%">
      <latex-image>
        <latex>
% TikZ styles (as in the TeX source)
\tikzstyle{startstop} =[trapezium, trapezium left angle=70, trapezium right angle=110,
  minimum width=1cm, minimum height=1cm, text centered, fill=red!30]
\tikzstyle{io} = [trapezium, trapezium left angle=70, trapezium right angle=110,
  minimum width=1cm, minimum height=1cm, text centered, fill=blue!30]
\tikzstyle{process} = [trapezium, trapezium left angle=70, trapezium right angle=110,
  minimum width=1cm, minimum height=1cm, text centered, fill=orange!30]
\tikzstyle{arrow} = [thick,->,>=stealth]

\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=2cm]
  \node(x)  [startstop] {$\vec x$};
  \node(bx) [io, below of=x] {$B\vec x$};
  \node(abx)[process, right of=x,xshift=4cm]{$AB\vec x$};

  \draw [arrow] (x) -- node[anchor=east] {\small Multiplication by $B$} (bx);
  \draw [arrow] (bx) -- node[anchor=north,xshift=1cm] {\small Multiplication by $A$} (abx);
  \draw [arrow] (x) -- node[anchor=south] {\small Multiplication by $AB$} (abx);
\end{tikzpicture}
        </latex>
      </latex-image>
      <shortdescription>Flow diagram comparing two ways to multiply matrices.</shortdescription>
      <description>
        Diagram showing two ways of getting from <m>\vec x</m> to <m>AB\vec x</m>, either by  <m>\vec x \mapsto B\vec x \mapsto AB\vec x</m> or by direct multiplication by <m>\vec x \mapsto AB\vec x</m>.
      </description>
    </image>

    <p>
      The product <m>AB\vec x</m> can be obtained either by multiplying by <m>AB</m>,
      or by multiplying by <m>B</m> and then by <m>A</m>. This corresponds to
      <em>composition of linear transformations</em>.
    </p>
  </page>



  <page xml:id="p-2-1-noncomm-example">
    <title>Example: Non-Commutativity</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-noncomm-with-A" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Let</p>
        <me>
          A=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 1\\
            0 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
        <p>
          Give an example of a <m>2\times 2</m> matrix <m>B</m> such that <m>AB\neq BA</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-2-1-transpose">
    <title>The Transpose of a Matrix</title>

    <definition xml:id="def-transpose">
      <title>Transpose</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The transpose <m>A^T</m> is the matrix whose columns are the rows of <m>A</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <example xml:id="ex-transpose-compute" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Compute:</p>
        <me>
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 5\\
            0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix}^T
        </me>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <theorem xml:id="ex-transpose-properties-fill" workspace="true">
      <title>Properties of Matrix Transpose</title>
      <statement>
        <ol>
          <li><m>(A^T)^T =</m> <m>A</m></li>
          <li><m>(A+B)^T =</m> <m>A^T + B^T</m></li>
          <li><m>(rA)^T =</m> <m>rA^T</m></li>
          <li><m>(AB)^T =</m> <m>B^TA^T</m></li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
  </page>

  <page xml:id="p-2-1-which-defined">
    <title>Example: Which Operations Are Defined?</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-which-operations-defined" workspace="true">
      <introduction>
        <p>Define</p>
        <me>
          A=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0
          \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          B=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 8
          \end{bmatrix},
          \qquad
          C=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 2 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 2
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Which of these operations are defined, and what are the dimensions of the result?
        </p>
    </introduction>
        <task workspace="true">
          <statement><p><m>A + 3C</m></p></statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="true">
          <statement><p><m>C(AB)^T</m></p></statement>
          </task>
        <task workspace="true">
            <statement><p><m>A + ABCB^T</m></p></statement>
        </task>
    </example>
  </page>

  <page xml:id="p-2-1-matrix-powers">
    <title>Matrix Powers</title>

    <p>
      For any <m>n\times n</m> matrix and positive integer <m>k</m>,
      <m>A^k</m> is the product of <m>k</m> copies of <m>A</m>.
    </p>

    <me>A^k = AA\cdots A.</me>

    <example workspace="true">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Compute <m>A^2</m> for <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp -2 \\ 5 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</me>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="ex-compute-c-power" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>Compute <m>B^8</m> for</p>
        <me>
          B=
          \begin{bmatrix}
            1 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 2 \amp 0\\
            0 \amp 0 \amp 2
          \end{bmatrix}.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>


  


  <page xml:id="p-2-1-additional-examples">
    <title>Additional Examples</title>
    <example xml:id="ex-tf-identity-factorization">
        <introduction>
            <p>
                <em>True or False.</em> If false, explain briefly.
            </p>
        </introduction>
      <task workspace="true">
        <statement>
        <p>
          For any <m>I_n</m> and any <m>A\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times n}</m>,
          <m>(I_n + A)(I_n - A) = I_n - A^2</m>.
        </p>
        </statement>
        </task>
        <task workspace="true">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For any <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}^{n\times n}</m>,
          <m>(A+B)^2 = A^2 + B^2 + 2AB</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </example>
  </page>

